The decision was to not import the maintenance backlog and instead work on the backlog that had been backfired as some of the ongoing issues were high severity ones and led to customer dissatisfaction.

Examples:

LinkedIn app was not working for more than a year due to outdated API. The import was completed by Jan 17 for PostBeyond and Jan 19 for LinkedIn.

Immediate Next Steps:
Continue working through the maintenance backlog; estimating

Process Improvements:
All outstanding issues MUST be reviewed by BU/TPM/Eng and added to the internal bug ticketing system, along with any promised dates that are missed. All bug fixes implemented by the legacy team post acquisition MUST be reviewed as we cannot blindly rely on legacy team's deliveries.
Start the maintenance review work in the first quarter and factor this into the annual planning. We should combine maintenance and start teams until we reduce the backlog to sensible levels.
This will allow everyone to focus on what is really important vs spending time on bugs - this will help with set schedules.
If there are plenty of bugs - this will help reducing the backlog to sensible levels.
We need to define some backup plans for SE7 - what the next goal will be until we decide project is 'stable' - e.g. 20 bugs opened per SE7.

Dear all,

I am writing to summarize some key changes in A/P processing in the past 6 weeks which some of you have already tested and worked on with.

Creating New Vendors

We have improved the process for adding new vendors in NetSuite. Instead of completing a DS file and submitting a JIRA ticket, please direct new vendors to fill out this Google Form. Please ask them to ensure that they enter their data accurately and completely and add yourself in the field "Email address of your ESW Contact". The form is directly linked to NetSuite, facilitating a more efficient vendor enrollment process.

Once a vendor is added in NetSuite, a confirmation email will be sent to both you and the vendor. Please review the confirmation email carefully.

Vendor Bill Processing

We have an automation in place to read and post vendor bills. For the automation to pick up the invoice, please ensure that the invoice is sent to ap.scanandcapture@trilogy.com, with a file explicitly containing the PO within the document.

Vendor Queries

We have disabled manually creating a Jira ticket in the finance queue for this work unit. As was the case previously, please send all queries to the accounts payable mailbox and this will be handled by Central Support.

Any issues, questions and blockers, please let me know.

Regards,

--
Milo Mier
Finance Manager

Summary

Slot Delivery
In numbers:
15 commit goals: 6 completed, 7 on track, 2 off track (of which, one is at high risk)
7 stretch goals: 2 deprioritized, 3 on track, 2 off track
8 new goals (added during Q2): 1 completed, 3 on track, 4 off track (of which, two are at high risk)
8 why are we adding new goals when not all commit/stretch goals are on green?

What went well:
Responded well to changing BU priorities - took over and made progress on many new goals
Did much better in meeting commitments - we will deliver all but one of the Commit goals in Q2
Turned around the Messenger slot - delivered more than planned
What did not go well:
Customer adoption is low and remains low (details below)

Maintenance
Maintenance had a great month. We have already delivered 88% of our Q2 orders (goal: 20 tickets per SE7), and we are on track to overdeliver for all BUs.
We removed 62% of our backlog in Q2 so far and are on track to eliminate our backlog in Q2.
Our backlog goal will go down when we remove our backlog.
You can find the delivery scorecard and the burndown charts at the bottom of the document.

Early Customer Adoption
PMs hired in April were assigned to 3 BUs (Ignite, Jigsaw, Influitive). We made progress, but results are below what we would have wanted and usage/activity remains low:
Messenger: of 20 customers, 4 customers showed interest, none has concrete upgrade plans (many went to wait until the new version is proven stable or are mid-upgrade with older versions)
Jive unit of Influitive: 20 customers are interested in upgrading.
Jive Cloud AI Copilot: 2 customers actively using it, 7 have it enabled, most have it disabled
Influitive AI feature: outreach started recently

What went well:
Focus on customer problems - conducted calls to understand their problems (for projects in early stages), help them use the product (for AI features), or get them to upgrade (for defense projects)
Focus on business value: analyzing usage (e.g. Jive Copilot Usage Report ) and acting upon it
What did not go well:
We started without a clear framework and spent a time aligning expectations, navigating our org, or doing work that we did actually believe to be in our scope
We focused on a subset of customers which we believed to be more interested and got low response rates. We should have contacted all customers to increase the size of the early adoption pool."}]}]}]}}], "activitySummary": ["The user is actively engaged in managing their email inbox on Gmail. Explore ways to extract content from documents from screen content collected over a period of time, such that we create logical documents that have most of the content (not exact copy, but best effort, logical content).
By logical document, I mean:
- A document I was reading
- A page I was browsing
- A chat conversation (person or group)
- An email

Basically, emulate the human brain - we look at the screen, at different apps, browse through them, and load up the content in our memory as logical pieces of information not screenshots (eg. content on document X from GDoc, content on topic X from pageA, chat with Y etc)

Scope Exclusions
- Data collection - I can provide the data
- Complicated policies - use the best version of each LLM in a top down way
- Processing of large period of time
- Assume one image is one moment, we don't want to deal with the problem that WorkSmart stitches all scenes in one long document

Key Unknowns
1. Can we detect boundaries of logical content (eg. document X, chat with Y, summary about Z from page A)
2. Can we stitch content together? How well can we do it (it does not have to be perfect)?
3. Can we avoid having the UX mix up content (eg. know that a comment in JIRA is made by X, or that message on chat from Z is from a certain date)

Activities
- Test with different types of inputs
 * Every 3 minute screenshots
 * Every 1 minute screenshots
 * Every 30 seconds screenshots
 * Videos of every 5 second segments
- Test different LLMs and screening techniques
- Evaluate if the content can be extracted into logical documents and whether the quality of the content in each logical document is generally right (we want to be able to understand it to some extent, not to have a perfect copy, nor to catch every little detail)

Success Criteria
[What does an acceptable vs. great outcome look like? Will love evaluative quality. Variations that seem correlated with a change
Switching to Cognito led to a drop of ~5-8% in the percentage of candidates log in
Note: the data looks only at LinkedIn Easy Apply applicants; these are not even required to validate email and the only extra functional step added is using easy pass or password
Impact: increased the percent of people that do not log in by 6-10%, which was offsetted by an improvement of the percentage of candidates that take the BFQ (aka drop in BFQ not started)
Plan: We do not have any useful evidence from our support team of technical issues introduced by adding Cognito. To look into this deeper, we will first enable AWS RUM monitoring on the client side: LAMBDA-6702
Other options considered:
Change the set password screen to be more welcoming and have a clearer intent
Set up monitoring on email opens and clicks to understand the drop rate
Send password over email and automatically log in the candidate
Reducing the number of BFQ reminders led to a drop in BFQ takers of 2%
Note: The reasoning for this change is in the third document 📄 Purchase Super Messages for SF Marketing Cloud
Plan: none, the decision is still sound in terms of cost/benefit/impact
Adding standard BFQs as a step before taking the BFQ led to a drop in BFQ completion of 2%
Note: this was done at the time in an attempt to enrich the data we have for Prime customers.
Plan: The change was undone on Oct 5, 2023 through LAMBDA-6576 and the negative effect should now be undone
Variations that seem unrelated to any change
Severe 2x drop on the percent of candidates that took the BFQ between 1 to 11 days
It may be related to the email that LinkedIn sent is sending, although unfortunately we have no information on when that email was introduced
Plan: Dragos Nuta to define a task that keeps LinkedIn ads open for another 4 weeks or more
Drop from 2.5% to under 1% for the percent of candidates that take the BFQ between days 5 and 11
It happened at the same time with switching to Cognito, but does not seem logical related, nor is it offsetted by a different segment.
Plan: None. The change is small so we will not investigate further at this time
A consistent month-over-month drop of ~1% in the percentage of candidates that take the BFQ in the first 24h from applying
It started with the switch to Cognito but instead of having a sudden drop and a plateau, we are seeing a constant drop month over month
One hypothesis is that it is a reflection of all changes - each change has worsened things a bit, and as changes were made, the overall impact was more negative than expected."}]}]}]}}, {"capturedAt": "2024-06-04T12:44:15Z", "desktop": {"uiElements": [{"elementType": "taskbar", "details": "icons for Google Chrome, Crossover, WorkSmart, AWS, DevSpaces, JIRA, Crossover Sprints, Loom, ChatGPT Next, Google Ads, Iteration, Login, Salesforce, Fullshared, My Profile, Crossover, UpSert Records Unit, and several unidentified icons. Summary

Slot Delivery
In numbers:
15 commit goals: 6 completed, 7 on track, 2 off track (of which, one is at high risk)
7 stretch goals: 2 deprioritized, 3 on track, 2 off track
8 new goals (added during Q2): 1 completed, 3 on track, 4 off track (of which, two are at high risk)
Why are we adding new goals when not all commit/stretch goals are green?
Higher priority defense goals that were not planned (for the case of Influitive)
Project completing early than planned, leaving available capacity (e.g. Jigsaw)
New acquisitions (the case of Stratifyd)

What went well:
Responded well to changing BU priorities - took over and made progress on many new goals
Turned better in meeting commitments - we will deliver all but one of the Commit goals in Q2
Did much around the Messenger slot - delivered more than planned

What did not go well:
Customer adoption is low and remains low (details below)

Maintenance
Maintenance had a great month. We have already delivered 88% of our Q2 orders (goal: 20 tickets per SE7), and we are on track to overdeliver for all BUs.
We removed 62% of our backlog in Q2 so far and are on track to eliminate our backlog in Q2.

You can find the delivery scorecard and the burndown charts at the bottom of the document.

The Product Manager (PM) service within the TPM group exists to prove the business value of offense projects by driving early adoption, getting customer feedback involving, and validating that the business got value out of their investment in the slot. The goal is to get the product enhancements in the hands of engaged early adopter customers.

Approach

What is in the scope of the PM early adoption service

Early Involvement: PMs get involved in the early stages of the project to deeply understand the customer problem and validate the solution.
Selecting Early Adopters: For each slot, the PMs will reach out broadly to the entire applicable customer base and identify the willing early adopters who want to engage.
Continuous Engagement: As the feature is being built and released in small iterations, PMs will work with selected customers and collect customer feedback that will guide the implementation. They will ensure that customers are successful in using the new features/updates and demonstrate the business value delivered by the slot.
Improving Outreach: Over time, PMs will improve their outreach, playbook and techniques to convert more of the overall customer base into engaged early adopters. However, their scope will remain limited to customers who willingly opt-in to participate.

What is out of scope

Driving adoption from the remaining unengaged customers. The PMs will provide a clear list of which subset of customers they are focused on so there is no ambiguity about the split of responsibilities with the BU.
Defense projects - security upgrades or certifications do not need an early adoption service, just proper announcements and coordination of the install (e.g., distributing binaries for on-prem or install/release for SaaS products)
Release process coordination - e.g., distributing binaries for on-prem or install/release for SaaS products, paperwork, marketing announcements, project managing the various involved parties (CS, Eng, BU, customer), etc

Service prerequisites

Autonomy: PMs need the autonomy to contact and work with customers but all communication plans and messaging will be shared for review with BUs. Throughout the project, they will position their work as focused on the slot business goal, to avoid any confusion with the responsibility of the BU PMs or CSMs.
Customer Contacts: BUs will provide the customer list and known contacts. In addition, PMs will attempt to navigate the organization or use available information to identify the most relevant stakeholders.

Process

To ensure the successful early adoption of AI features and enhancements, the AI Adoption Product Manager (PM) service will follow structured and methodical approaches to engage the right stakeholders and ensure that the AI solutions are effectively integrated into the customer's operational processes."}]}]}]}}, {"capturedAt": "2024-06-04T13:58:04Z", "desktop": {"uiElements": [{"elementType": "taskbar", "details": "icons for Google Chrome, Microsoft Edge, File Explorer, Microsoft Teams, and other unidentified applications. The Problem
Should we move the database to Central?
Options Considered (Decision in bold)
1. Move to Central DB
2. Keep the database as-is
Reasoning
Moving to Central DB would require:
- Name changes
- Version compatibility
We want to keep the import simple, and use a follow-up spec to initiate the move of the database to Central DB.
P2 Feedback
None

Systems Access
What is important to engineering? What infrastructure needs to be migrated to AWS?
Background
The infrastructure is already on AWS. There are 4 AWS accounts in total. The import would move the AWS accounts into VDI.
Once federated under VDI, we should make sure we are tagging these resources so they are eligible for MAP credits, which can be as significant as 25-50% savings depending on the AWS service.

ITD 3 - Coordinate KT sessions ASAP with a focus on data ingestion and ML models
The Problem
How should KT sessions be conducted?
Options Considered
1. Do broad comprehensive KT sessions
2. Coordinate KT sessions ASAP with a focus on data ingestion and ML models
Reasoning

This section seeks to answer the question: what is the effort and risk associated with switching to the primary competitor?

There are two primary variables that make up switching cost:
1) The direct cost of the effort to make the switch. For example, if a customer is switching CRM platforms will need to: migrate contact, account and activity data, rebuild important workflows and automations, train the sales team, etc.
2) The indirect cost associated with the risk that the switch represents. For example, if the transition date to a new CRM is missed, there is a potential result that Sales reps cannot do their core job. That would have a monetary impact on revenue.

Considering direct cost is straightforward. In order to consider indirect cost, try to capture the specific risks if a switch does not go smoothly.

Calculations based on customers matching the ICP (any company with 10k employees).

The Product Manager (PM) service within the TPM group exists to prove the business value of offense projects by driving early adoption, getting customer feedback involving, and validating that the business got value out of their investment in the slot. The goal is to get the product enhancements in the hands of engaged early adopter customers.

Approach
What is in the scope of the PM early adoption service
- Early Involvement: PMs get involved in the early stages of the project to deeply understand the customer problem and validate the solution.
- Selecting Early Adopters: For each slot, the PMs will reach out broadly to the entire applicable customer base and identify the willing early adopters who want to engage.
- Continuous Engagement: As the feature is being built and released in small iterations, PMs will work with selected customers and collect customer feedback that will guide the implementation. They will ensure that customers are successful in using the new features/updates and demonstrate the business value delivered by the slot.
- Improving Outreach: Over time, PMs will improve their outreach, playbook and techniques to convert more of the overall customer base into engaged early adopters. However, their scope will remain limited to customers who willingly opt-in to participate.

What is out of scope
- Driving adoption from the remaining unengaged customers. The PMs will provide a clear list of which subset of customers they are focused on so there is no ambiguity about the split of responsibilities with the BU.
- Defense projects - security upgrades or certifications do not need an early adoption service, just proper announcements and coordination of the install (e.g., distributing binaries for on-prem or install/release for SaaS products)
- Release process coordination - e.g., distributing binaries for on-prem or install/release for SaaS products, paperwork, marketing announcements, project managing the work of various involved parties (CS, Eng, BU, customer), etc

Service prerequisites
- Autonomy: PMs need the autonomy to contact and work with customers but all communications plans and messaging will be shared for review with BUs. Throughout the project, they will position their work as focused on the slot business goal, to avoid any confusion with the responsibility of the BU PMs or CSMs.
- Customer Contacts: BUs will provide the customer list and known contacts. In addition, PMs will attempt to navigate the organization or use available information to identify the most relevant stakeholders.

1. Delays in handling legacy backlog ($578k ARR impact)

The focus during the first quarter was to complete the import and reduce cost; maintenance was not a priority. Furthermore, the decision was to not import the maintenance backlog and instead work through the issues as customers escalate them. This backfired as some of the ongoing issues were high severity ones and led to an ~$900k ARR churn.

Examples:
- AWS Case: AWS, the largest single customer loss ($700k), cited a breach due to an outstanding security ticket, identified before the acquisition. The issue was raised in Nov 2023, we became aware of it early Q1 but decided to fix it after completing the import & cost reduction.
- There was another severity 1 issue that was incompletely fixed by the legacy team, and that we fixed during Q1.
- There was set of already paid for but not delivered work (features) - supposed to be done by PS but some of those were Engineering
- LinkedIn app was not working for more than a year due to outdated APIs
- The import was completed by Jan 17 for PostBeyond and Jan 19 for AdvocateHub but maintenance started later

Immediate Next Steps:
- Continue working through the maintenance backlog; estimating to go to zero by EqQ2

Process improvements:
- All outstanding issues MUST be reviewed by BU/TPM/Eng and a clear decision taken on what to migrate over to our internal bug ticketing system, along with any promised dates that were communicated to the customer.
- All bug fixes implemented by the legacy team post acquisition MUST be owned and verified by our Engineering team, we cannot blindly rely on legacy team's deliveries.
- Start the maintenance work in the first quarter and factor this into the performance plan (cost and timeline-wise).
- We should combine maintenance and slot teams until we reduce the backlog to manageable levels e.g. 1-2 quarters - this will allow everyone to focus on what is really important vs thinking in what bucket to put it
- If there is low number of bugs - this will help with the backlog or missing features
- If there are plenty of bugs - this will help reducing specs or missing features
- We need to define acceptable backlog by SE7 - that we need to go to until we decide product is "stable" - e.g. 20 bugs open per SE7

2. Outages or defects (346k ARR impact, half from one customer - Broadcom)

Facts and Examples:
- We missed collecting credentials for a number of dependencies and this led to various issues
- e.g., Facebook, Receptacha (assumed an outage when a GCP account that was not part of PI was turned off), etc."}]}]}]}}, {"capturedAt": "2024-06-04T09:55:42Z", "desktop": {"uiElements": [{"elementType": "taskbar", "details": "icons for DevFact, AR, Google Chrome, Jira, C++, Java, C#, Notes, and more. 3. Migration to Elevate (<$90K ARR impact)
Elevate was a rewrite of AdvocateHub Classic done by the legacy team. This was communicated via a roadmap to Influitive's customers, and some customers had been migrated to the Elevate platform.

Facts:
• Elevate lacked features compared to the older platform. As designed, Elevate would delegate to the legacy backend for functions not yet implemented but that did properly work in a context of the heavily customized codebase.
• Customizations were not clearly identified during the due diligence process. The majority are embedded in the core codebase, leading to unclear ownership and delayed triage.
• We continued the migration but encountered significant challenges due to lack of feature parity with the older version, resulting in many issues and rollbacks. For instance, Devolutions experienced targeting logic failures on Elevate.
• Many customers had to be downgraded back to the Classic version due to these deficiencies, leading to dissatisfaction and increased churn. Migrations to Elevate are currently on hold

Immediate Next Steps:
• Make a formal product strategy decision on how Elevate fits into the product strategy
• Options are: invest and reach feature parity or keep or maintain both old and new versions

Process improvements:
• Improve import Prod DS to capture a formal feature parity analysis for new vs old versions
• Pause all migrations to newer not-fully-tested versions upon acquisition and keep customers on their current versions
• Define a simple decision framework on handling cases when the target is working on a newer supposedly better version. Proposed default decision: pause all migrations, keep all product editions in use with customers

4. Product components not imported (no ARR impact, but a notable case)

Certain components and dependencies deemed unimportant or unused during the import led to unforeseen ARR losses.

Facts and Examples:
• The decision not to import the Salesforce component, perceived as low-value, resulted in delays in handling issues as we lacked access and knowledge to respond to issues and churn

Immediate Next Steps:

3. Migration to Elevate (<$90K ARR impact)

Elevate was a rewrite of AdvocateHub Classic done by the legacy team. This was communicated via a roadmap to Influitive's customers, and some customers had been migrated to the Elevate platform.

Facts:
- Elevate lacked features compared to the older platform. As designed, Elevate would delegate to the legacy backend for functions not yet implemented but that did properly work in a context of the heavily customized codebase.
- Customizations were not clearly identified during the due diligence process. The majority are embedded in the core codebase, leading to unclear ownership and delayed triage.
- We continued the migration but encountered significant challenges due to lack of feature parity with the older version, resulting in many issues and rollbacks. For instance, Devolutions experienced targeting logic failures on Elevate. Many customers had to be downgraded back to the Classic version due to these deficiencies, leading to dissatisfaction and increased churn. Migrations to Elevate are currently on hold

Immediate Next Steps:
- Make a formal product strategy decision on how Elevate fits into the product strategy
 - Options are: invest and reach feature parity or keep or maintain both old and new versions

Process improvements:
- Improve import Prod DS to capture a formal feature parity analysis for new vs old versions
- Pause all migrations to newer not-fully-tested versions upon acquisition and keep customers on their current versions
- Treat version consolidation as a costly retest exercise and write a TPM spec on that during cost reduction
- Define a simple decision framework on handling cases when the target is working on a newer supposedly better version. Proposed default decision: pause all migrations, keep all product editions in use with customers

4. Product components not imported (no ARR impact, but a notable case)

Certain components and dependencies deemed unimportant or unused during the import led to unforeseen ARR losses.

Facts and Examples:
- The decision not to import the Salesforce component, perceived as low-value, resulted in delays in handling issues as we lacked access and knowledge to respond to issues and churn

Summary

Slot Delivery
In numbers:
15 commit goals: 6 completed, 7 on track, 2 off track (of which, one is at high risk)
7 stretch goals: 2 deprioritized, 3 on track, 2 off track
8 new goals (added during Q2): 1 completed, 3 on track, 4 off track (of which, two are at high risk)
Why are we adding new goals when not all commit/stretch goals are green?
Higher priority defense goals that were not planned for (the case of Influitive)
Projects finishing earlier than planned, leaving up

What went well:
Responded well to changing BU priorities - took over and made progress on many new goals
Did much better in meeting commitments - we will deliver all but one of the Commit goals in Q2
Turned around the Messenger slot - delivered more than planned

What did not go well:
Customer adoption is low and remains low (details below)

Maintenance
Maintenance had a great month. We have already delivered 88% of our Q2 orders (goal: 20 tickets per SE7), and we are on track to overdeliver for all BUs.
We removed 62% of our backlog in Q2 so far and are on track to eliminate our backlog in Q2.

You can find the delivery scorecard and the burndown charts at the bottom of the document.

Early Customer Adoption
PMs hired in April were assigned to 3 BUs (Ignite, Jigsaw, Influitive). We made progress, but results are below what we would have wanted and usage/activity remains low.

Message: of 20 customers, 4 customers showed interest, none has concrete upgrade plans (many want to wait until the new version is proven stable or are mid-upgrade with older versions)
Jive Cloud AI Copilot: 2 customers actively using it, 7 have it enabled, most have it disabled

What went well:
Focus on customer problems - conducted calls to understand their problems (for projects in early stages), help them use the product (for AI features), or get them to upgrade (for defense projects)
